data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, EF Core's Cosmos DB provider **deprecated** synchronous query execution and let you opt in via `CosmosOptionsExtension` to keep it working. In .NET 11, **that opt-in is removed entirely**. All four of your sync calls will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime:

| Sync (breaks) | Async (required) |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(…)` | `.FirstAsync(…)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

The Cosmos DB SDK is inherently async — there is no true synchronous path. The sync APIs were always doing sync-over-async (`GetAwaiter().GetResult()`), risking deadlocks.

## Fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- Remove the sync-over-async opt-in from your `DbContext` configuration — it's no longer recognized.
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods, propagating `async` up the call stack.
- `Add()` stays synchronous (it only tracks in memory); the actual I/O happens in `SaveChangesAsync()`.
